public class PassByVal {
    static void tryChange(int n) {
        n = 999; // changes the COPY only
        System.out.println("Inside: n = " + n);
    }
    static void changeArray(int[] arr) {
        arr[0] = 999; // changes the ACTUAL array
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int x = 5;
        tryChange(x);
        System.out.println("Outside: x = " + x); // still 5!
        int[] nums = {1, 2, 3};
        changeArray(nums);
        System.out.println("Array[0] = " + nums[0]); // 999!
    }
}

key_concepts.explanation:
DRY means: if you write the same (or very similar) code more than once, extract it into a method. Repeated code is a bug waiting to happen -- if you fix it in one place but forget another, you have inconsistent behaviour.

Before DRY (bad):
  System.out.println('====================');
  // ... code ...
  System.out.println('====================');
  // ... more code ...
  System.out.println('====================');

After DRY (good):
  static void printLine() { System.out.println('===================='); }
  printLine(); code(); printLine(); moreCode(); printLine();

How to spot DRY violations:
  1. Copy-pasting code? Extract a method.
  2. Same logic with different values? Make a method with parameters.
  3. Same pattern in multiple places? One method, many calls.

Benefits: Fix bugs in ONE place. Change behaviour in ONE place. Test in ONE place. Read in ONE place.

